  "entries": [
    {
      "type": "context",
      "agent": "user",
      "content": "# ARCHITECT PLAN OVERVIEW\n**Plan**: Investigate and fix missing 'annunci' link extraction in routes.ts\n**Description**: The crawler fails to find links on target pages due to a type cast bug (Attr.value returning undefined) and an unfiltered XPath. This plan adds debugging, fixes XPath filtering, corrects the type cast, improves scroll strategy, adds retry logic, and validates the fix on real pages.\n## All Steps\n1. **Debug link extraction: add logs and check real elements**: ## Goal\nIdentify why the crawler finds zero links containing 'annunci' on the target page, even though manual inspection shows them.\n\n## Task Type\nDebugging & Investigation — add temporary instrumentation to `src/routes.ts` to capture actual page state and DOM elements at runtime.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\nThe default handler in `src/routes.ts` (lines ~55-70) currently:\n1. Scrolls the page to `min(totalHeight * 0.3, 800)` (line 56).\n2. Waits 2 seconds (line 57).\n3. Uses `page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(...)` to extract href values (line 63).\n4. Casts each element to `Attr` and accesses `.value` (line 63) — this returns `undefined` for all `<a>` elements.\n5. Logs `Found ${hrefs.length} links containing \"annunci\"` even though no filtering is applied (line 67).\n6. Filters `hrefs` with `.filter(h => h?.toLowerCase().includes('annunci'))` (line 68) — but all hrefs are `undefined`, so the result is always empty.\n\nThe target page is provided via `request.url` from input `startUrls[]`.\n\n## Action\n1. Open `src/routes.ts` and locate the default request handler (around line 50-80).\n2. Add the following temporary instrumentation **after** the existing scroll and wait (after line 57):\n   - `console.log('🔍 Page URL:', request.url);`\n   - `console.log('📐 Scroll position:', await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollY));`\n   - `console.log('📏 Page height:', await page.evaluate(() => document.body.scrollHeight));`\n   - Take a full-page screenshot and save it to `screenshots/debug-fullpage.png` using `await page.screenshot({ path: 'screenshots/debug-fullpage.png', fullPage: true });` (create the directory if needed).\n3. Replace the existing link extraction block (lines 63-69) with a debug version that:\n   - Evaluates all `<a>` elements and returns an array of objects: `{ href: el.getAttribute('href'), text: el.textContent?.trim() }`.\n   - Logs the total number of `<a>` elements found, and the number of those whose href or text contains `'annunci'` (case-insensitive).\n   - Logs the first 10 such annunci-like elements with both href and text.\n4. Keep the dataset push unchanged (url + title).\n5. **Do not fix the underlying bugs yet** — only add diagnostic output.\n6. Run the crawler locally with the target URL(s) from the input and observe the terminal output and screenshot.\n\n## Reasoning\nThis step isolates the root cause by verifying: whether the page loads correctly, whether `<a>` elements exist, whether the scroll reaches the region containing annunci, whether `getAttribute('href')` returns values vs. the current buggy `Attr.value`, and why the filter produces zero results. The screenshot provides visual confirmation.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- Use `page.evaluate()` or `page.locator().evaluateAll()` consistently. For the debug extraction, call:\n```typescript\nconst allLinks = await page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(\n    (els) => els.map(el => ({\n        href: el.getAttribute('href'),\n        text: el.textContent?.trim()\n    }))\n);\n```\n- Filter with:\n```typescript\nconst annunciLinks = allLinks.filter(l =>\n    (l.href && l.href.toLowerCase().includes('annunci')) ||\n    (l.text && l.text.toLowerCase().includes('annunci'))\n);\n```\n- Add a check: if `annunciLinks.length === 0`, log a warning and also print the full `allLinks` array (or first 30) to inspect the actual href values.\n- Ensure the screenshot path is writable (local run: `mkdir -p screenshots` before running).\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `page.screenshot` fails (e.g., no permission), log a warning and continue.\n- If the page does not load because of the crawling context, the error will be caught by Crawlee's retry module. Ensure the log still appears before any crash.\n- If `getAttribute('href')` returns `null` (anchor without href), these should be included but filtered out later.\n\n## Validation\n- Run the crawler with `npx tsx src/main.ts` and provide an input JSON containing the target URL (e.g., `{ \"startUrls\": [\"https://example.com/annunci\"], \"maxRequestsPerCrawl\": 1 }`).\n- Check the logs: you should see the page URL, scroll position, page height, total `<a>` count, annunci link count, and the first few annunci links.\n- If annunci link count is still 0, examine the full list of `<a>` elements from the logs to see if they contain 'annunci' in href or text, and verify the screenshot shows annunci elements visually.\n- After verifying the logs, revert the debug changes later (the next step will fix the bugs).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- `src/routes.ts` — existing router file.\n- Input JSON with `startUrls` pointing to the target page with annunci links.\n- Local environment: Node 20+, npm dependencies installed, Camoufox binary fetched (see Dockerfile).\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not change the dataset output schema (url + title).\n- Do not modify any other files (main.ts, tests, etc.).\n- Keep the step focused on debugging only — do not implement the eventual fixes.\n- All new logging must use `console.log` for clarity (Apify log is okay but console.log works for local debug).\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\nTemporary screenshots and full link dump may be heavy on large pages. For debug runs with single URL this is acceptable. Remove the instrumentation after debugging.\n\n## Documentation Impact\nAfter this step, document the findings (e.g., in a comment or a brief summary) so the next developer understands why the zero-link issue occurred.\n2. **Fix XPath to filter links containing 'annunci'**: ## Goal\nModify the XPath in `src/routes.ts` to correctly select only links whose `href` attribute contains the substring \"annunci\", instead of selecting all links with any `href`.\n\n## Task Type\nCode fix in existing scraping logic.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **File**: `src/routes.ts`, line 63 (approximately) in the default handler.\n- **Current code**:\n  ```typescript\n  const hrefs = await page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(\n      (els) => els.map((el) => (el as unknown as Attr).value),\n  );\n  ```\n- The XPath `//a[@href]` selects **every** `<a>` element that has an `href` attribute, regardless of its value. The subsequent log statement (line 67) incorrectly claims \"Found ${hrefs.length} links containing \\\"annunci\\\"\", but no filtering on \"annunci\" is actually performed.\n- The type cast `(el as unknown as Attr).value` is a separate bug (being fixed in step `fix-type-cast-getattribute`), but the XPath filter must be corrected **now** to ensure the right links are selected once the cast is fixed.\n\n## Action\nModify the XPath in the `page.locator` call to include a predicate that filters for `href` containing the string \"annunci\". Additionally, update the log message to accurately reflect the filtering done.\n\n## Reasoning\nThe current XPath selects all `href`-bearing links, which dilutes the extraction to potentially hundreds of irrelevant links (e.g., navigation, footer). The target use case requires links that point to \"annunci\" (listings/advertisements). By narrowing the XPath, we reduce noise and ensure that only relevant links are considered for further processing. This is the first step in the core extraction fixes; after the type cast bug is resolved, the filtered links will be correctly extracted.\n\n## Implementation Details\n1. Open `src/routes.ts` and locate the line with `'xpath=//a[@href]'` (around line 63).\n2. Change the XPath to: `'xpath=//a[contains(@href, \"annunci\")]'`\n3. Update the log message (likely on the same or next line) from:\n   `context.log.info(`Found ${hrefs.length} links containing \"annunci\"`);`\n   to:\n   `context.log.info(`Found ${hrefs.length} links with href containing \"annunci\"`);`\n4. Keep the existing `evaluateAll` callback as-is (the type cast bug will be fixed separately).\n\n**Important**: Do not change the callback logic (e.g., `.getAttribute('href')`) here – that belongs to the next step.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If the page contains no links with \"annunci\" in the href, `hrefs` will be an empty array. The log will correctly report 0 links. This is acceptable behavior.\n- If the page structure uses text content or different attribute names (e.g., `data-href`), the XPath filter may miss them. However, the step is specifically about filtering by `href` containing \"annunci\". Future enhancements (like retry with progressive scroll) may address lazy-loaded links.\n- The XPath is case-sensitive. If the target site uses uppercase or mixed-case \"Annunci\", the filter will not match. To account for that, consider using `translate()` or a case-insensitive XPath, but the initial fix should assume lowercase as per the user's context. This can be adjusted later if needed.\n\n## Validation\n- Run the crawler locally against a page known to contain links with \"annunci\" in their href. Example: `npx tsx src/main.ts` with appropriate start URL.\n- Check the log output: it should show a count that is less than or equal to the total number of links on the page.\n- Verify that the extracted `hrefs` array (when the type cast is later fixed) contains only those links whose href includes \"annunci\". For now, the array will still be `undefined` due to the cast bug – that's expected and will be resolved in the next step.\n- If unit or integration tests exist for the route, adjust them to expect the filtered count (or skip them temporarily until the cast fix is merged).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- This step depends on `debug-current-extraction`, which should have confirmed that the unfiltered XPath extracts many irrelevant links and that the log message is misleading. No other code changes are required before this step.\n- The step `fix-type-cast-getattribute` will follow and fix the `.value` bug to make the extracted hrefs meaningful.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not modify any other files or add new dependencies.\n- Maintain ESM imports and `.js` extensions if re-exporting.\n- Follow project code conventions (4-space indent, single quotes, Prettier formatting).\n- The change must not introduce TypeScript or lint errors.\n- After the change, the log statement must be truthful about the filtering.\n3. **Replace Attr.value cast with getAttribute('href')**: Step details are being generated.\n4. **Enhance scroll depth to trigger lazy-loaded annunci**: Step details are being generated.\n5. **Retry extraction with progressive scroll if no links found**: Step details are being generated.\n6. **Update tests and validate on real target pages**: Step details are being generated.",
