tContent?.trim() }`.\n   - Logs the total number of `<a>` elements found, and the number of those whose href or text contains `'annunci'` (case-insensitive).\n   - Logs the first 10 such annunci-like elements with both href and text.\n4. Keep the dataset push unchanged (url + title).\n5. **Do not fix the underlying bugs yet** — only add diagnostic output.\n6. Run the crawler locally with the target URL(s) from the input and observe the terminal output and screenshot.\n\n## Reasoning\nThis step isolates the root cause by verifying: whether the page loads correctly, whether `<a>` elements exist, whether the scroll reaches the region containing annunci, whether `getAttribute('href')` returns values vs. the current buggy `Attr.value`, and why the filter produces zero results. The screenshot provides visual confirmation.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- Use `page.evaluate()` or `page.locator().evaluateAll()` consistently. For the debug extraction, call:\n```typescript\nconst allLinks = await page.locator('xpath=//a[@href]').evaluateAll(\n    (els) => els.map(el => ({\n        href: el.getAttribute('href'),\n        text: el.textContent?.trim()\n    }))\n);\n```\n- Filter with:\n```typescript\nconst annunciLinks = allLinks.filter(l =>\n    (l.href && l.href.toLowerCase().includes('annunci')) ||\n    (l.text && l.text.toLowerCase().includes('annunci'))\n);\n```\n- Add a check: if `annunciLinks.length === 0`, log a warning and also print the full `allLinks` array (or first 30) to inspect the actual href values.\n- Ensure the screenshot path is writable (local run: `mkdir -p screenshots` before running).\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `page.screenshot` fails (e.g., no permission), log a warning and continue.\n- If the page does not load because of the crawling context, the error will be caught by Crawlee's retry module. Ensure the log still appears before any crash.\n- If `getAttribute('href')` returns `null` (anchor without href), these should be included but filtered out later.\n\n## Validation\n- Run the crawler with `npx tsx src/main.ts` and provide an input JSON containing the target URL (e.g., `{ \"startUrls\": [\"https://example.com/annunci\"], \"maxRequestsPerCrawl\": 1 }`).\n- Check the logs: you should see the page URL, scroll position, page height, total `<a>` count, annunci link count, and the first few annunci links.\n- If annunci link count is still 0, examine the full list of `<a>` elements from the logs to see if they contain 'annunci' in href or text, and verify the screenshot shows annunci elements visually.\n- After verifying the logs, revert the debug changes later (the next step will fix the bugs).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- `src/routes.ts` — existing router file.\n- Input JSON with `startUrls` pointing to the target page with annunci links.\n- Local environment: Node 20+, npm dependencies installed, Camoufox binary fetched (see Dockerfile).\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not change the dataset output schema (url + title).\n- Do not modify any other files (main.ts, tests, etc.).\n- Keep the step focused on debugging only — do not implement the eventual fixes.\n- All new logging must use `console.log` for clarity (Apify log is okay but console.log works for local debug).\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\nTemporary screenshots and full link dump may be heavy on large pages. For debug runs with single URL this is acceptable. Remove the instrumentation after debugging.\n\n## Documentation Impact\nAfter this step, document the findings (e.g., in a comment or a brief summary) so the next developer understands why the zero-link issue occurred.\n\nThis is the ONLY task you must complete in this iteration. Do not work on other steps.",
